prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: 3C273 polarization at 1mm
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Full-polarization observations of 3C273 in band 6 to detect Faraday rotation over the band.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: This is the standard setup for band 6 full-polarization observations that are done in continuum mode.
The observations can be performed at any configuration because 3C273 is a quasar and we are interested in the polarization of the bright center of the source.

The sensitivity is dictated by a high S/N detection of the polarization at each individual 1.875 GHz base-band. We estimate the total intensity to be 5.7 Jy based on an ALMA observation of 3C273 in Dec 2014. We need a sensitivity of 5 mJy to obtain 0.1% sensitivity in polarization degree. Because we want to reach this in each 1.875 GHz baseband, we set the sensitivity requirement to 2.5 mJy, which would be reached in just a few seconds. The total integration time is long because this is a full polarization experiment so we are parallactic angle rather than sensitivity limited.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We apply for 3hrs of ALMA time in the full polarization mode to study the magnetic fields and the plasma density in and/or around the innermost part of the jet in the nearest quasar 3C273 at 1mm. Taking advantage of the wide bandwidth of the ALMA band 6, we aim to measure the Faraday rotation effect across the band in order to look for the predicted extremely high rotation measures (RM) of $> 10^5$rad/m$^2$. Combining the Faraday rotation information with the (frequency-dependent) polarization fraction we will distinguish between Faraday rotation happening inside or outside of the emission region. In the case of internal rotation, the measurements would provide important constraints on the jet magnetic field and the low-energy particle population close to the jet base. In the case of external Faraday screen, the observations would probe the physical conditions in either the jet boundary layer or the broad line region surrounding the jet.
